bios.Pbcd5dde: William Edward Acraman.  Bristol iron-monger, engine manufacturer and boiler-maker. Member of town council and Merchant Venturers. Director of the Great Western Steamship Company.  Acraman supplied the axle for the paddle wheels in the Great Western steamship.
bios.P2aee50c: William Bruce Adair.  Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pd937ae7: John Barnes. Mechanical engineer who built steeple engines.    Brunel sought his endorsement for this engine design in propeller-driven ships - a design rejected by both marine engineers and the Royal Navy .  No evidence of support.
bios.Pcdb690b: Sir John Barrow, Secretary to the Admiralty, 1840-45.
bios.P15896b8: J. P. Bartum. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pfaad904: J. Bates. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P1ecbfc0: Thomas Kington Bayly.  Business Partner and nephew of Phillip John Miles of Miles, Harford & Co. Bank, Bristol. Trustee of the Great Western Steamship Company at first inception.
bios.Pd2ba266: Thomas Baynton. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P0780cd0: Robert Bright.  Member of Bristol merchant family historically linked to Caribbean trade.  Business partner of George Gibbs from 1823.  Bright was a major investor in, and director of, the Great Western Railway and a principal director and shareholder of the Great Western Steamhip Company. In 1850, the firm of Gibbs, Bright Company acquired the Great Britain, and operated the vessel for the next 26 years.  Bright received extensive government compensation paid to former slave owners after the abolition of slavery: https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/41207
bios.P8cc4424: Isambard Kingdom Brunel.  Consulting engineer for the Bristol Dock Company. Chief engineer of the Great Western Railway and other southern branch lines.  Managing consultant for the Great Western Steamship. Consulting engineer for the Great Britain Steamship.  Investor in both Great Western Railway and Great Western Steamship. Co.  Provided critical connection to, and super-intedenace of, Joshua Field's marine engineering work in the Great Western.  Persuaded Great Western Steamship Company to adopt screw propeller in the Great Britain, and was appointed by Royal Navy to examine early iterations of the technology.
bios.P385f0ba: Henry Bush.  Member of Bristol merchant family.  President of Bristol Chamber of Commerce immediately prior to the founding of the Great Western Steamship companies.  Bush was a director of both the Great Western Steamship Company and Great Western Railway.  He received a jointly dispersed compensation payment from the British goverment after the abolition of slavery, believed to be linked to John Cobhams estate:  https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/45209
bios.Pa7082f3: Captain Walcott, Royal Navy.  Shareholder of Greaty Western Steamship Co. Advocate of Bath interests in the company.
bios.Pbb42f2b: W H Castle.  Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P79956f9: Captain Chappel.  Controller of Channel Packets, Royal Navy.  Corresponded of both Brunel and pioneering iron ship-builder John Laird during propeller trials of Archimedes.  Later Secretary of the Royal Mail, who purchased the Great Western on his advice.
bios.P4528099: J B Clarke.  Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P705780c: Christopher Claxton. Claxtons father was a Caribbean merchant, with the family trading business passing to Christopher's older brother, William, who was also a senior member of the Society of Merchant venturers. As a second son, Christopher took up a career in the services, and was a sailor in Royal Navy during Napoleonic wars.  He was latterly a ship captain for both William Patterson and Thomas Guppy, and was ppointed harbour master in 1834.  He was Managing Direcor of Great Western Steamhip Company from inception, and provided the company with useful contascts in the Royal Navy.  His
bios.P69ec796: William Claxton.  Elder brother of Christopher Claxton.  Inheritor of family business.  Member of Merchant Venturers (historical appointers of harbour master), treasurer of Merchant Venturers from 1841-73.  Trustee of the Great Western Steamship Company at its inception.  William Claxton received compensation payment from the British government after the abolition of slavery:  https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/1722518733
bios.P98542f9: Joseph Cookson. Member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce.  Trustee of the Great Western Steamship Company.  Legal owner, with four other trustees, of Great Western Steamship.
bios.P38182c9: Captain Jackson, Royal Navy.  Assisted with docking and surveying of the Great Western after its first year of service.
bios.Paccb3d4: Captain Crozier, Royal Navy. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.  (1840)
bios.P4ffe37c: Thomas Cruttwell.  Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pfd23970: James Cunningham. Bristol merchant, shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.  Cunningham had links to numerous Caribbean plantations and received compensation from the British state after the abolition of slavery: https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/46762
bios.Pca664dc: Bryan Donkin.  Inventor and mechanical engineer. Pioneer of early factory production processes, including food canning (1809).  Met Marc Brunel during his work at Chatham Docks. Mutual associate of Maudslay, Sons & Field.  Served as Director of Thames Tunnel.  Asked by Isambard Brunel to survey and review early trunk engine designs for the Great Britain steamship, which was obliged.
bios.P2b0d33b: Mr Dowell. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pcbd922a: William Fairbairn.  Mechanical and civil engineer and pioneer of iron shipbuilding from 1830.  Supplied vessels to both P&O and the Royal Navy during the mid 1830s.  Consulted by Brunel on construction techniques early in the process of building the Great Britain.
bios.P91702aa: F. H. Falkner.  Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P86db8e0: Joshua Field.  Mechanical Engineer.  Partner in Maudlsay, Sons & Field from 1822, specialising in marine engines, steam engines and other machinery.  Founding member of Institute of Civil Engineers.  Designed and built engines and boilers of the Great Western steamship.  Built engines for Great Britain Steamship after a protracted process as builder of last resort.  Closely embedded with naval architecture and marine engineering community on the River Thames.
bios.Pb56b2a9: Dr Charles Fox.  Bath-based shareholder of the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pf4322a5: Charles Bowles Fripp.  Member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce.  Director of the Great Western Railway.  Auditor of the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P7d0a5aa:
George Gibbs.  Member of merchant family historically linked to Caribbean trade.  Business partner of Robert Bright from 1823 onward.  Member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce, director and major investor in Great Western Railway, and shareholer in the Great Wetsern Steamship Company.  Gibbs retired in 1839, although the family trading house, Gibbs, Bright Company acquired the Great Britain, and operated it for 26 years.  The parent company of Gibbs, Bri=ght, Anthony Gibbs & Co., acquired and operated the vessel from 1882 gto 1886.  George H Gibbs, also listed here, was Georges cousin, and son of Anthony Gibbs.  George received partial payments in compensation from the British state after the abolition of slavery, through joint and counterclaims to various estates:  https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/2725
George H Gibbs.  Son of Anthony Gibbs of Tyntesfield, and cousin of George Gibbs, who was an investor in and later nominal owner of the Great Britain.  George H Gibbs was an associate of Brunel as a major investor in the Great Western railway, in which he was closely involved.  He was also an investor in the Great Western Steamship company, and was given a private tour of Maudslay & Fields engines construction for the the Great Western when on business with Brunel in London.
bios.P3459f8e: Henry Godwin.  Appointed director of the Great Western Steamship Company in 1838.
bios.P1530830: John Grantham.  Pioneering iron shipbuilder, based in Liverpool.  Built several small coastwise and river iron steamers and published a treatise on Iron ship building in 1842.  Corresponded closely with Guppy and Brunel during construction of the Great Britain.  Mutual associate of the Rennies.  Designed the first Atlantic iron screw steamer to be launched after the Great Britain, the Sarah Sands, in 1847.
bios.P621419c: Thomas Guppy.  Bristol sugar merchant and manufacturer.  Founding member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce.  Founding member of the Great Western Railway.  The original projector of the Great Western Steamship concept.  Director of Great Western Steamship Company from first inception.  Appointed superintending engineer of the company in 1841.
bios.Pd3270d7: Samuel Hall.  Boiler maker for marine steam engines.  Condensing principles adopted by close associate Joshua Field for the boilers of the Great Western.   Admonished by Brunel for claiming that Field gained contracts through favouritism.
bios.P77c70f2: John Hare. Member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce.  Shareholder in Great Western Steamship Company. Political oponent of Christopher Claxton.
bios.P9bba97a: John Harford.  Partner of Philip John Miles in the bank Miles, Harford & Co., which was the bank of both the Great Western Railway and Great Western Steamship Company.  Trustee of the Great Western Steamship Company. Legal owner, with four other Trustees, of Great Western Steamship.
bios.Be4e3595: Hoare & Barnetts.  London solicitors of both the Great Western Railway and Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P7b1217c: Francis Humphries.  Hired as superintending engineer on the great Britain Steamship.  In constant friction with Brunel over engine design, who disliked Humphres trunk engine.  Died in 1841, suceeded by Thomas Guppy.
bios.P6cdc195: Richard Irvin.  Agent for the Great Western Steamship Company in New York.  Responsible for receiving incoming freights and brokering return freights and tickets, fuel supplies and crewing.
bios.Pc730405: A.P. Johnson. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P1ef8f5e: Thomas Kingsbury.  Trustee of the Great Western Steamship Company at first inception. Legal owner, with four other trustees, of Great Western Steamship.
bios.P9e1efbc: Thomas Kington. Merchant with close links to Caribbean trade. Member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce. Magistrate and Sheriff for Bristol, 1836.  Chair of Bristol Reformation Society.  Selected Deputy Chair of the Great Western Steamship Company at first inception, and was variously chair or beputy chairman during the construction of the Great Britain.  Kington was also a partner in the bank of his father in law, Philip John Miles, the Great Western Steamship co.'s bankers in Bristol.  Kington was awarded extensive compensation by the British state after the abolition of slavery, and, as with Gibbs, Bright Company, re-directed merchant trading to the Antipodes after emancipation: https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/44502
bios.P21c3f2c: John Laird.  Pioneering iron ship builder based in Birkenhead, Liverpool.  Correspondent of William Fairbairn and Edward Chapell.  Chapell informed Laird that the Great Western Steamship Company would adopt a propeller design during the Archimedes trials.  Younger brother, MacGregor Laird, was chief engineer to the Great Western Steamship Company's first rival, the British & American Steam Navigation Company.
bios.P9613c6e: Oliver Lang.  Master Shipwright and later surveyor for the Royal Navy, based at Woolwich.  Lang developed earlier innovations of Chief Surveyor to the Admiralty, Robert Seppings, of adding diagonal cross-strapping to wooden hulls, substituting wooden straps for Iron.  This development was adopted in the Great Western .  Lang was thanked by the great Western Company for his 'liberal' advice by the company.  Also a mutual associate of Joshua Field.
bios.P43a4c2d: Mr. Levy.  Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P0ba1593: Miss Lucas.  Assumed partner of Samuel Lucas.  Shareholder in Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pb46a47f: Samuel Lucas. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P883f966: George Lunnell.  Director of Bristol Steam packet Company.  Member of Chamber of Commerce. Director of Bristol Dock Company.  Advocate for large scale steam shipping in Bristol.  Director of rival Atlantic steamshipping company British & American Steam Navigation.
bios.P4367563: Peter Maze.  Vice President of Bristol Chamber of Commerce. Director of Great Western Railway.  Director of Bristol Dock Company.  Chairman of the Great Western Steamship Company at its inception.  Maze was an unsuccesful claimant for compensation after the British abolition of slavery: https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/-811541867
bios.B459ad2c: Miles, Harford & co. Bank. Brsitol-based bank serving the Great Western Railway, Great Western Steamship Company, and several private individuals and enterprises associated with the steamship company.  Miles being Phillip John Miles, richest contemporary citizen of Bristol.  Miles received extensive compesation payment from the British state after the abolition of slavery: https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/19118
bios.P2d26c03: W. Morgan. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P742bf21: John Moxham.  Bristol-based accountant with promises on Corn Street.  Auditor of the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P7245e39: Cpt. W. Hamilton Royal Naval Officer.
bios.Pf6fc03e: Mr Harding. Member of Chamber of Commerce. Shareholder in Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P92d6d97: John Edye.  Senior Constructor in the Royal Navy, deputy to William Symonds. Advocate for Great Western Steamship company within the Admiralty.
bios.P14cedb4: G. Norman. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.B94a5fc3: Osborne, Ward & Sons.  Bristol-based solicitors for the Great Western Railway and Great Western Steamship Company.  Robert Osbourne was the frequent recipient of Brunel's Bristol-bound letters from London.  Jeremiah Osborne, the family patriarch, was also a major shareholder in the Great Western Railway, and received compensation from the British state after the abolition of slavery:  https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/26642
bios.P1acdd25: William Edward Parry.  Controller of Steam at the Royal Navy.  Brunel's most frequent correspondent during Archimedes and Rattler trials.
bios.P7ac918b: William Patterson.  Bristol Ship-builder.  Drew lines of and constructed hulls for both the Great Western and Great Britain steamships.
bios.P3f1aed3: Thomas Pycroft.  Bath-based barrister and shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pe052c16: George Rennie.  London-based mechanical engineer and manufacturer.  Rennie was a founding member of the screw propeller company, which built the Archimedes in order to showcase the potential of Francis Petit Smith's Screw.  Rennies workshop build the engines for the Archimedes. Brunel maintained relations with Rennie regarding both marine and civil engineering issues, but did not seek written advice on the steamship projects.
bios.P1bdd7ad: Richard Robinson. Member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce. Shareholder in great Western Railway Company.
bios.P4a8aecf: Robert Scott.  Prominent Bath-based businessman. Director of Great Western Steamship Company and major investor in Great Western Railway.
bios.B5f61bba: Marine engineering company.  Advice sought by Brunel on ways to minimise required engine-space in steam vessels.
bios.P48c423a: Mr Smith. Shareholder in Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pf7e2cc1: Francis Petit Smith. Original patentee of succesful screw-propelling configuration, adopted by the screw propeller company for the prototype ship Archimedes.  Frequently conversant with brunel in both Archimedes and Rattler trials.
bios.Pa75d4fc: John Stafford. Shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pe581cb4: Mr Stedder.  Bath-based investor in Great Western Railway and Great Western Steamship.
bios.B420a61a: Swain, Stevens & Co.  London-based solicitors for the Great Western Railway and Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P854f908: William Symonds.  Surveyor of the Royal Navy from 1830-1847.  Immediate superior of Oliver Lang.  Thanked by Great Western Steamship Company for liberal assistance with Great Western steamship.  Corresponded with Brunel throughout propeller trials.
bios.P2e7a6f1: John Taylor.  Member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce.  Shareholder in Great western Steamship Company.
bios.P7cdd6a7: Reverend Taylor. Shareholder in Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pd8adb76: John Vining.  Member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce.  Member of Merchant Venturers.  Director of Great Western Railway.  Trustee of Great Western Steamship Company.  Legal owner of the Great Western steamship.
bios.Pa0eacdd: Mr Warr. Shareholder in great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P40a375e: Thomas Boneville Were.  Director of Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.Pb2a06fa: John Winwood.  Bristol marine engineer.  Tendered to build engines for Great Western, unsuccessful. Briefly auditor of Great Western Steamship Compnay, 1838-9.  Retired 1840.
bios.P7fe128f: Robert Young.  Marine engineer and mutual correspondent of Brunel and John Laird.
